                Mount Olympus is the highest mountain in Greece, rising majestically near the Aegean coast at the border between
                Thessaly and Macedonia. The mountain is a massive limestone massif formed approximately 200 million years ago
                during the Triassic period, shaped by tectonic uplift and extensive erosion. Its dramatic peaks, deep gorges,
                and near-vertical cliffs create an imposing presence that has inspired awe throughout human history.
            </p>

